'''Jordan David Kovacs''' (born June 12, 1990) is an [[American football]] [[safety (American football position)|safety]] who played his [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] sophomore season in [[2010 Michigan Wolverines football team|2010]] for the [[Michigan Wolverines football]] team.  He was a [[walk-on]] who earned 2009 [[College Football News|CollegeFootballNews.com]] Freshman All-America second team recognition and 2009 ''[[Sporting News]]'' Freshman All-Big Ten honors for the [[2009 Michigan Wolverines football team|2009 Wolverines]] while being the second-leading [[tackle (football move)|tackler]] on the team. Granted a scholarship for his second year, he was the second-leading tackler in the [[Big Ten Conference]] and was selected as a [[2010 Big Ten Conference football season|2010 All-Conference]] honorable mention.

==Background==
Kovacs attended [[Clay High School (Oregon, Ohio)|Clay High School]], which was the rival high school of current Wolverine teammate [[Kevin Koger]].<ref name=JKTHS />  In high school, he earned [[varsity letter]]s in [[basketball]] as a sophomore and junior.  He also earned All-City recognition in [[track and field]] three times (first team as a senior, second team as a junior and honorable mention as a sophomore) and was a four-year letterman.  He qualified for the Ohio State championships in the [[4x400 meter relay]].  He was a three-year letterman in football, where he earned All-Ohio academic honors and All-district honors as both a [[wide receiver]] and [[defensive back]].<ref name=32JK/> 

He was not recruited by any [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] schools as a [[high school football]] player, but he was recruited by some [[Division II (NCAA)|Division II]] schools and was considered as a preferred walk-on at the [[University of Toledo]].<ref name=JKTHS>{{cite web|url=http://michigan.scout.com/2/912120.html|title=Jordan Kovacs Tells His Story|accessdate=2010-11-05|2009-10-22|work=GoBlueWolverine}}</ref>  Electing to attend Michigan even though he would not receive an athletic scholarship, he was initially [[waitlist]]ed at the school and was finally admitted in June.<ref name=WOWJKRHRtRT/>

==College career==
He did not make the [[2008 Michigan Wolverines football team|2008 Wolverines]] due to a knee problem, but was advised to try out again after his knee healed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequad.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/playing-time-for-a-walk-on/?scp=2&sq=%22Jordan+Kovacs%22&st=nyt|title=Playing Time for a Walk-On|accessdate=2010-11-05|date=2009-09-13|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Evans, Thayer}}</ref>  He had surgery to repair [[cartilage]] damage, but that did not alleviate his problems.<ref name=WOWJKRHRtRT/>  After discovering a torn [[meniscus]], he had a second knee surgery, which was successful.<ref name=JKTHS/>  

In 2009, he was one of the most highly regarded walk-ons in the nation.<ref name=WGFNSTSS>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1050279|title=Walk-ons Go From No Stars To Shining Stars|accessdate=2010-11-05|date=2010-02-10|publisher=[[Rivals.com]]}}</ref> His debut on September 5 against the [[2009 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]] was on [[special teams]].<ref name=32JK/> The following week he registered 31 plays against [[2009 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] after starting safety Michael Williams suffered leg cramps.<ref name=WOWJKRHRtRT>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/091709aab.html|title=Walk-On Wonder: Jordan Kovacs Relishes His Rags-to-Riches Tale|accessdate=2010-11-05|date=2009-09-17|author=Howard, Leah|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> He made his first start on September 26 against [[2009 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]].<ref name=32JK/> On October 3 of that season, he had 17 tackles against [[2009 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]] in the annual [[Paul Bunyan Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/player/gamelog?playerId=384589&year=2009|title=Jordan Kovacs  #32  S (2009 game log)|accessdate=2010-11-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  He posted ten tackles and made his first career [[interception]] on November 14 against [[2009 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]].<ref name=32JK/>  That season he played [[free safety]] before being switched to [[strong safety]].<ref name=JKTHS/>  He started one game at free safety and seven at strong safety over the course of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/2009fbt.htm|title=2009 Football Team|accessdate=2011-01-19|date=2010-03-26|publisher=The Regents of the University of Michigan /[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>  He finished the season as the second leading tackler for the [[2009 Michigan Wolverines football team|2009 Wolverines]].<ref name=WGFNSTSS/> He earned 2009 [[College Football News|CollegeFootballNews.com]] Freshman All-America second team recognition and 2009 ''[[Sporting News]]'' Freshman All-Big Ten honors.<ref name=32JK/>  He was also a [[Rudy Award]] candidate.<ref name=32JK/>

Kovacs earned a [[scholarship]] at the beginning of the [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/michigan-safety-jordan-kovacs-is-more-comfortable-sees-defensive-improvements-coming/|title=Michigan safety Jordan Kovacs is more comfortable, sees defensive improvements coming|accessdate=2010-11-05|date=2010-09-22|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Arnold, Jeff}}</ref>  In the second game of the season on September 11 against [[2010 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] in the [[Michigan <U+2013> Notre Dame football rivalry]] game, Kovacs recorded his first interception of the season and second of his career as part of a 10-tackle effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=302540087|title=Michigan  28 (2-0, 1-0 away); Notre Dame 24 (1-1, 1-1 home)|accessdate=2010-11-28|date=2010-09-11|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=JKNCAA/> On October 16 he recorded 2.5 tackles for a loss against [[2010 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|Iowa]].<ref name=32JK/> After eight games in the 2010 season he ranked second in the [[2010 Big Ten Conference football season|Big Ten Conference]] in [[tackle (football move)|tackles]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5tybyAFFu|archivedate=2010-11-03|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/football/exec/rankingSummary?year=2010&org=418|title=Michigan (5 - 3)|date=2010-10-30|accessdate=2010-11-03|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref> On November 18, he was nominated for the [[Burlsworth Trophy]], which was a newly created award for the most outstanding player to have begun his career as a walk on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwahomepage.com/fulltext/?nxd_id=200197|title=Nominees Announced for Inaugural Burlsworth Trophy|accessdate=2010-12-08|date=2010-11-18|publisher=Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc.}}</ref> On November 20, he posted his first career [[quarterback sack]] during a season-high twelve tackle performance against [[2010 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]].<ref name=JKNCAA>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/mfb/playerDetail.jsp?yr=2010&org=418&player=32|title=Team: Michigan - Year: 2010 Thru 11/20/10 - Player: Jordan Kovacs - Uniform #: 32 Position: DB Class: SO|accessdate=2010-11-21|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref>  With one week remaining on the conference schedule, the performance tied Kovacs for third-overall in the Big Ten, gave Kovacs a wide lead among Big Ten [[Underclassman (student)|underclassman]] (8.64 vs. 7.55 per game over the next highest performer) and extended his lead among Big Ten defensive backs (8.64 vs 8.27).<ref name=112010BTR>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uPHVIonM|archivedate=2010-11-21|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/mfb/2010/Internet/conf%20stats/2010000000827PD.HTML|title=Big Ten Player Report|date=2010-11-20|accessdate=2010-11-21|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref> In the final game of the regular season on November 27 against [[2010 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in the annual [[Michigan <U+2013> Ohio State football rivalry]] game, Kovacs recorded his second interception of the season and third of his career as part of a 17-tackle effort.<ref name=JKNCAA/>  He collected a career-best 41 [[return yards]] following the interception.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=303310194|title=Michigan  7 (7-5, 3-5 Big Ten); (8) Ohio St 37 (11-1, 7-1 Big Ten)|accessdate=2010-11-28|date=2010-11-27|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> In the game, Kovacs tied a career-high with 17 total tackles including a new career-high 9 solo tackles.<ref name=JKNCAA/>  Kovacs ended the [[2010 Big Ten Conference football season]] ranked second in the conference to teammate [[Jonas Mouton]] in tackles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/stats/2010-2011/confldrs.html|title=The Automated ScoreBook: 2010 Big Ten Conference Team Statistics Through games of Jan 07, 2011|accessdate=2010-01-07|date=2010-01-07|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/mfb/2010/Internet/conf%20stats/2010000000827PD.HTML|title=Big Ten Player Report|accessdate=2011-01-13|date=2011-01-10|publisher[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref> Following the Big Ten Conference season, he was selected as an honorable mention All-Conference selection by the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-football/michigans-denard-robinson-named-big-tens-offensive-player-of-the-year-other-wolverines-honored/|title=Michigan's Denard Robinson named Big Ten's Offensive Player of the Year, other Wolverines honored|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|accessdate=2010-11-30|date=2010-11-29|author=Bigelow, Pete}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/112910aae.html|title=Big Ten Announces 2010 Football All-Conference Teams and Individual Honors|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=2010-11-30|date=2010-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/112910aaa.html|title=Robinson Named Big Ten Offensive Player of the Year|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=2010-11-30|date=2010-11-29}}</ref>

==Personal==
His father Louis, who was a walk-on for Michigan coach [[Bo Schembechler]],<ref name=CLafshaU>{{cite web|url=http://toledoblade.com/article/20101124/SPORTS17/11230396/-1/SPORTS18|title=City League alumni find second home at UM: Kovacs, Koger earn spots The Game|accessdate=2010-12-08|date=2010-11-24|work=[[Toledo Blade]]|author=Autullo, Ryan}}</ref> lettered for the [[1982 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref name=32JK>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/kovacs_jordan00.html|title=32 Jordan Kovacs|accessdate=2010-11-05|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> His family regularly brought him to watch Michigan home games when he was growing up.  The family regularly sat in Section 27 of [[Michigan Stadium]], on the north side of the press box.  Today the family sits underneath the scoreboard, since they have a son on the team.<ref name=CLafshaU/>

